### How we built these charts
Methodology for creating these data visualizations:

1. Identify which comments are in each key tension
We started by labelling each comment with which of the five key tensions (if any) they relate to. We used an AI tool (the Snowflake Cortex Classify Text Large Language Model) to do this labeling. 
2. Process and restructure the comments data
For each comment, we used another AI tool (Claude 3.5 Sonnet LLM) to summarize the comment and measure its relationship to the key tension it is paired with. We did this in order to make sure we were plotting only the most relevant parts of the comment. We then converted those summaries into numerical data (called "semantic embeddings") that represent the meaning of the comments in a way a computer can understand and process. We did this using Snowflake Cortex Embed Text 1024.
3. Finding sub-categories
We used the BERTopic framework to organize comments by their similarities and sort them into different groups based on common topics. 
This involved reducing the dimensionality of the comments using UMAP. We also performed density-based clustering with HDBSCAN, with algorithm parameters specifically tuned for each key tension to optimize topic delineation.
4. Labeling the sub-categories
 After grouping the comments by topic, we used the 'Claude 3.5 Sonnet' model again to give each group a short label (usually 2-5 words) that captures the main idea or viewpoint of that group.
5. Plotting the comments

Finally, we used a topic-supervised UMAP, tuned per key tension to reduce all that numerical data into two simple coordinates. This allows us to plot everything on a 2D chart, where the comments are color-coded based on their topic, making it easy to see the patterns and relationships.

